<DocsLayout title="Calendar Systems - Balinese Calendar" description="Overview of the Balinese calendar systems">
	<h1 class="font-display text-4xl gold-accent mb-8">Calendar Systems</h1>

	<p class="text-lg mb-6">
		The Balinese calendar system is a complex combination of several different calendar systems that have been used in Bali for centuries. Understanding these systems is essential for proper use of the Balinese Calendar library.
	</p>

	<h2 class="font-display text-2xl text-balinese-gold mt-12 mb-6">Overview</h2>

	<p class="mb-6">The Balinese calendar combines:</p>

	<ol class="list-decimal list-inside space-y-2 mb-8">
		<li><strong>Saka Calendar</strong> - A lunar calendar system</li>
		<li><strong>Pawukon Cycle</strong> - A 210-day ritual cycle</li>
		<li><strong>Wewaran Systems</strong> - Various week-based cycles</li>
		<li><strong>Gregorian Calendar</strong> - For civil date correspondence</li>
	</ol>

	<h2 class="font-display text-2xl text-balinese-gold mt-12 mb-6">Saka Calendar (Lunar Calendar)</h2>

	<p class="mb-4">The Saka calendar is the official lunar calendar used in Bali:</p>

	<ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-2 mb-8">
		<li><strong>Year length</strong>: 354 or 355 days (lunar year)</li>
		<li><strong>Months</strong>: 12 lunar months (Sasih)</li>
		<li><strong>New Year</strong>: Usually falls in March</li>
		<li><strong>Epoch</strong>: Started in 78 CE</li>
	</ul>

	<h2 class="font-display text-2xl text-balinese-gold mt-12 mb-6">Pawukon Cycle</h2>

	<p class="mb-4">The Pawukon is a unique 210-day cycle that runs independently of the lunar calendar:</p>

	<ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-2 mb-8">
		<li><strong>Duration</strong>: 210 days (30 weeks of 7 days)</li>
		<li><strong>Purpose</strong>: Determines ritual days and ceremonies</li>
		<li><strong>Components</strong>: Multiple overlapping cycles</li>
	</ul>

	<h2 class="font-display text-2xl text-balinese-gold mt-12 mb-6">Wewaran Systems</h2>

	<p class="mb-4">Wewaran are the various week-based systems that operate simultaneously:</p>

	<ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-2 mb-8">
		<li><strong>Saptawara</strong> (7-day) - Most commonly used</li>
		<li><strong>Pancawara</strong> (5-day) - Important for market days</li>
		<li><strong>Sadwara</strong> (6-day) - Used for certain ceremonies</li>
		<li><strong>Astawara</strong> (8-day) - Less common</li>
		<li><strong>Sangawara</strong> (9-day) - Rarely used</li>
		<li><strong>Dasawara</strong> (10-day) - Special ceremonial purposes</li>
	</ul>

